Betty,<br>
     Would like to add my thanks for your post.  Have been tryning to get a nurse vet here in Philly to get on this site, but she's been very tied up helping veterans get jobs at her day job, and being executive director of our area's Homeless Veterans' Standdown after hours.<br>
    <br>
To everyone,<br>
     Commented on Kali on site #50 today.<br><br>
     From a number of contacts on the net over two months, I've become rather concerned over what I perceive as a lack of balance in those who are teaching on Vietnam.  When I go into a high school; I make a point of touching on views both to the right and to the left of mine, and make clear that their is still no clear consensus of opinion on many aspects of the war after all these years. I feel I owe it to the students to let them know that their are serious moral issues about which people still disagree, and that while I have valid experiences and knowledge to share with them, my &quot;war&quot; differed from others', my knowledge and experience is limited and there are many other sources to learn from and understand. The teacher, who isn't aware that there is much one doesn't know or understand or that one has limitations, scares me; because rather than teaching one's students how to think and grow, one will shackle them with the limitations one doesn't acknowledge.
<p><code>-- gerald _ney@icpphil.navy.mil  (Gerald Ney, &quot;professor&quot;, 7/68-7/69) </code><p>


